Photo by The Telegraph on December 06, 2020. Image may contain: one or more people, people standing, tree, plant, sky and outdoor, text that says 'I haven't spent Christmas with myfamily for 11 years'. After Kate Young moved to the UK from Australia, she discovered the unique pleasures of being adopted by friends for Christmas:⁠
⁠
"The run-up to my first Christmas as an ‘orphan’ in London was spent with my Aussie flatmates, working through every British Christmas cliché we could imagine – carol singing, yule logs, a huge tree in our very non-huge Whitechapel flat… Then I headed to the Cotswolds for the day itself, to spend Christmas with my surrogate British parents"⁠
⁠
What are your Christmas traditions?⁠
⁠
🎄 Click the link in our bio to read more 🎄⁠
⁠
#christmas #xmas #uk #australia #london⁠ #family #friendship⁠

node.accessibility_caption:
Photo by The Telegraph on December 06, 2020. Image may contain: one or more people, text that says 'Hannah and Terence try... indoor-skiing 'I didn't ski as a child because we weren't posh enough' HEAD'. He’s a lifelong skier. She’s more Bambi on ice. This is what happened when our intrepid couple columnists took to the slopes of Hemel Hempstead.⁠
⁠
Hannah:  I have always associated skiing with being one of the many ways in which rich people choose to top themselves. We cover sidestepping, snowploughs, speed adjustments, changing direction, and something called ‘independent linking of turns’, which I appear able to do not entirely voluntarily. I’m not bad.⁠
⁠
Terrence:  I grew up skiing and what I’ve most been looking forward to is the mansplaining. I head to the big-boy slope. We ski down to motivational Coldplay. As indoor pistes go, it is impressively long; as mountain pistes go, it’s not. ⁠
⁠
⛷️ To read more, click the link in our bio ⛷️⁠
⁠
#couple #relationship #ski #skiing #hemelhempstead⁠

node.accessibility_caption:
Photo by The Telegraph on December 06, 2020. Image may contain: one or more people and people standing, text that says 'Tosca Musk on sperm donors, starring in a Beyoncé video and her brother Elon'. You've heard of Elon Musk, the second-richest person in the world and the man behind Tesla, PayPal and SpaceX.⁠
⁠
But he's not the only Musk with a story to tell.⁠
⁠
Tosca, is the younger sister of the tech tycoon, and the founder of Passionflix – a Netflix-esque streaming service specialising in erotic adaptations of bestselling romance novels.⁠
⁠
When launching her business, she didn't consider asking Elon, who's worth an estimated $128 billion, for a loan.⁠
⁠
She says: "If my brother just gave me the money, there’s nothing to prove"⁠
⁠
The siblings were not born into wealth. Their single mother Maye worked five jobs to support the family. Having been a model for five decades, the matriarch has found her greatest success in later life: starring in a Beyoncé video, appearing nude on the cover of Time magazine and becoming the oldest spokesmodel for CoverGirl.⁠
⁠
She raised Tosca to think that women can do the same as men, and even helped her daughter pick a sperm donor before twin boys, Isabeau and Grayson, were born.⁠
⁠
"I always believed in making things happen and still do. When somebody says, 'That’s impossible,' you’ll even hear my kids say, 'Anything is possible.'"⁠
⁠
If past generations of Musks are anything to go by, the world better watch out⁠
⁠
⭐ To read the full article, click the link in our bio⁠ ⭐⁠
⁠
#elonmusk #toscamusk #tesla #spacex #paypal #family #business #beyonce #covergirl #romancenovels⁠

node.accessibility_caption:
Photo by The New York Times on December 06, 2020. Image may contain: 1 person, standing, hat and outdoor. Barbra Streisand is, as ever, firmly in control.

Since her breakout in the 1960s, the singer and actor has been able to persuade the world around her to listen — not by chasing trends but by remaining always and fully herself.

“I still think I’m like most creative people are — confident at times and insecure at times,” @barbrastreisand told @tmagazine. “I don’t know if that ever goes away.”

Nearly her entire adult life has been chronicled in images — onscreen and in photographs — and she’s the subject of scores of unauthorized biographies, none of which she’s read. She’s won Oscars, a Tony, Emmys, even the Presidential Medal of Freedom. And for 6 years, she’s been working on an autobiography that she says is nearing completion.

But any story about her life must begin with her singing voice: “one of the natural wonders of the age, an instrument of infinite diversity and timbral resource,” as Glenn Gould, the celebrated classical pianist, once put it. Streisand famously has had no serious musical education. She says her ability to hold a note can be largely attributed to one quality: willpower.

Tap the link in our bio to read more about Streisand’s art collecting, philanthropy and political activism. Photo by @collierschorrstudio.

node.accessibility_caption:
Photo by The New York Times in Quintana Roo. Image may contain: one or more people and outdoor. There is a race against time to save one of Mexico’s battered coral reefs from climate change.⁣
 ⁣
In an unusual experiment, a coral reef, which runs 28 kilometers south of Cancún, is now insured against hurricanes. The policy provides money for a team of locals known as “the Brigade” to repair corals, piece by piece, in the days after storms.⁣
 ⁣
The Brigade, an assortment of tour guides, diving instructors, park rangers, fishermen and researchers, are “like paramedics,” said María del Carmen García Rivas, a leader of the group and director of the national park that manages the reef.⁣
 ⁣
“The more days that pass, the less chance they have of survival,” she added.⁣
 ⁣
The race to repair the reef is more than an ecological fight; it’s also a radical experiment in finance. The reef could be the first natural structure in the world with its own insurance policy. And this year, Hurricane Delta’s force triggered the first payout — about $850,000 to be used for the reef’s repairs.⁣
 ⁣
In this area of Mexico, like so many parts of the world, humans have weakened coral, tiny tentacled animals that secrete layers of limestone to build outer skeletons for themselves. Rising sea temperatures, ocean acidification, sewage pollution and overfishing leave coral more vulnerable to hurricane damage.⁣
And hurricanes themselves are becoming more severe because of climate change. This year, the Atlantic has seen the most named storms on record.⁣
Tap the link in our bio to read more about the team’s efforts to restore the reef, and how environmentalists and insurance companies behind the policy hope it becomes a model for protecting other far-flung coastlines. Photo by @danielberehulak⁣
